<h2 class="section-head">The 100% Kona vs. <em>Kona-blend trap</em></h2>

<p class="body">This is the single most important consumer-protection fact in Kona coffee, and most buyers have no idea it exists. Hawaii state law allows any bag labeled "Kona blend" to contain as little as 10% actual Kona coffee. The other 90% can be literally anything: low-grade Central American commodity beans, Brazilian Robusta, leftover roaster sweepings. As long as 10% of what is inside the bag came from the Kona coast, the brand can put the word Kona on the front, charge a premium versus a regular blend, and call it legal.</p>

<p class="body">Most of the bags you see at Honolulu airport gift shops, on cruise ship duty-free racks, and in mainland grocery store coffee aisles are 10% blends. They use the Kona name to charge $15 to $25 for what is structurally a generic commercial blend with a small Hawaiian topping. If the label does not say the phrase "100% Kona" in plain English, it is not 100% Kona. Period. There is no other label that means the same thing. "Kona blend," "Kona style," "Kona roast," "Hawaiian Kona blend," and "made with real Kona" all mean somewhere between 10% and 90% of the bag is not Kona at all.</p>

<div class="callout">
  <p>The rule has exactly one form. If the bag does not say "100% Kona Coffee" on the front, treat it as a blend. Treat the price tag accordingly.</p>
</div>

