<h2 class="section-head">How to tell if <em>your Kona is real</em></h2>

<p class="body">Four checks. Run them in this order and you will almost never get fooled.</p>

<ul class="body-list">
  <li><strong>The label must say "100% Kona Coffee."</strong> Not "Kona blend." Not "Kona-style." Not "Hawaiian Kona blend." The exact phrase "100% Kona" or "100% Kona Coffee" is the only label Hawaii law treats as a guarantee.</li>
  <li><strong>Look for the Hawaii Department of Agriculture grade marking.</strong> Authentic Kona is officially graded as Peaberry, Extra Fancy, Fancy, Number 1, Select, or Prime. A bag with no grade marking is suspicious.</li>
  <li><strong>Price floor: anything under $30 per pound is almost certainly fraudulent.</strong> The cost of producing real 100% Kona, even before margin, is higher than that. A $15 "Kona" bag is mathematically impossible to be 100% Kona.</li>
  <li><strong>Sourcing transparency.</strong> The seller should be willing to name the specific farm, co-op, or estate the beans came from. Real Kona producers are proud of their farms. Counterfeiters are vague.</li>
</ul>

<p class="body">Apply the same logic to any premium origin claim. If a bag of <a href="/learn/what-is-peaberry-coffee" style="color: var(--gold); text-decoration: none;">peaberry coffee</a> does not name the farm and the harvest year, and the price looks too low to be real, it is probably not what the label says it is.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">How to brew Kona to <em>actually taste it</em></h2>

<p class="body">Spending $50 a pound on Kona and brewing it through a stale paper filter with boiling water out of a kettle is a small tragedy. Three brewing rules will preserve what you paid for.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">Grind</h3>
<p class="body">Medium grind for drip coffee makers. Slightly finer for pour-over. Coarser, sea-salt sized, for French press. Always grind right before brewing. Pre-ground Kona loses its aromatic top notes within days, which is exactly the part of the cup the price tag is paying for.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">Water temperature</h3>
<p class="body">200 degrees Fahrenheit for medium roast Kona. Boiling water (212 F) scorches the delicate chocolate and citrus notes and brings out bitterness. If you do not have a temperature-controlled kettle, boil water and let it sit off heat for 30 to 45 seconds before pouring.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">Ratio</h3>
<p class="body">Standard 1:16 coffee-to-water ratio by weight. Roughly 30 grams of coffee per 480 grams of water. Strong enough to show body, light enough to show the brighter notes. Adjust to taste, but start there.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">Method recommendation</h3>
<p class="body">French press is particularly good for Kona Peaberry. The denser, rounder peaberry bean handles longer immersion without over-extracting, and the metal mesh filter preserves the natural oils that carry the milk chocolate and hazelnut notes. Pour-over is the cleanest expression for Private Reserve and Estate, especially V60 with a slow, even pour. Drip is fine if it is your daily method, just use the right water temperature.</p>

<div class="callout">
  <p>One simple rule for all Kona, regardless of method: never use pre-ground Kona from a bag that has been open more than a week. The flavor difference between freshly ground and stale ground at this price point is enormous, and it is the most common reason buyers conclude Kona is "overrated."</p>
</div>

<h2 class="section-head">Where Kona fits in the <em>broader Hawaiian coffee picture</em></h2>

<p class="body">Hawaii is the only U.S. state that commercially produces coffee, but Kona is not the only Hawaiian origin worth knowing. Ka'u, on the southern slopes of the Big Island, is the rising star and the connoisseur's pick. Maui produces coffee from the slopes of Haleakala, often with a brighter, more wine-like profile. Molokai, Kauai, and the Hamakua coast of the Big Island all produce smaller quantities. A bag labeled simply "Hawaiian coffee" is not the same thing as a bag labeled "100% Kona," and a sampler is the easiest way to taste the differences without committing to a full pound of each. For the full island-by-island breakdown and how Kona compares to other premium origins, the <a href="/learn/kona-coffee-guide" style="color: var(--gold); text-decoration: none;">Kona coffee guide</a> is the parent reference.</p>

<p class="body">Kona's signature is balance, not intensity. It will not deliver the wild bergamot and jasmine of an Ethiopian washed Yirgacheffe, the syrupy blueberry of an Ethiopian natural, or the funky tropical fruit of a Panama Geisha. What it delivers is a uniquely smooth, low-acid, never-aggressive cup with a soft chocolate and nut backbone, the kind of coffee that wins over people who normally find specialty coffee too harsh. That is the personality you are paying for, and that is why authentic 100% Kona has held its price for decades while other premium origins have come and gone from the spotlight.</p>

